data.content:
This is a known **C# 14 breaking change**: the new `Span<T>` overload resolution rules.

## What happened

In C# 14, `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. This is fine in regular code, but **expression trees cannot represent `Span<T>`-based methods**, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` (or use `.AsEnumerable()`) to force the compiler to pick `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Before (.NET 9) — binds to Enumerable.Contains, works fine
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.Contains(num);

// After (.NET 10) — force Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Or use the static method directly:
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches prevent the compiler from binding to the `MemoryExtensions` span overload, keeping the call representable in an expression tree.
